<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is crochet gauge?", answer: "Crochet gauge is the number of stitches and rows per a given area of crocheted fabric, usually measured over 4 inches or 10 centimeters. Gauge depends on your yarn, hook size, stitch type, and personal tension. Getting the right gauge is what makes a wearable garment fit and a blanket come out the size it was designed to be." },
  { question: "Why do I need turning chains?", answer: "When you work crochet in rows, the first stitch of each new row needs extra height so it reaches the top of the previous row. Those extra chains at the start of a row are called turning chains. Single crochet needs 1 turning chain, half double crochet needs 2, double crochet needs 3, and treble crochet needs 4. The starting chain at the very beginning of a project also adds the same extra chains to set up the height of the first row." },
  { question: "Does gauge matter for a scarf?", answer: "Gauge matters less for a scarf than for a fitted garment, but it still affects fabric density, drape, and how much yarn you use. If you crochet loosely with a small hook the fabric will feel stiff; if you crochet tightly with a large hook it will be holey. Even scarves benefit from swatching for feel, even if the exact dimensions are flexible." },
  { question: "How do I match a pattern's gauge exactly?", answer: "Work a swatch with the yarn and hook the pattern recommends, wash and block it the way you will treat the finished project, then measure. If you have too many stitches per inch, go up a hook size. If you have too few, go down a hook size. Keep adjusting until the stitch count matches. Row gauge is harder to match and is usually less critical since patterns tell you to work to a measurement." },
  { question: "Should I count the turning chain as a stitch?", answer: "It depends on the stitch type and the pattern. For double crochet and treble crochet, the turning chain is often counted as the first stitch of the row. For single crochet, the turning chain is almost never counted. Always follow what the specific pattern tells you, because counting a turning chain inconsistently throws off your stitch count." }
]) %>

